title: Exclude a few python tests for the DML EP
body:
**Description**: 

Some Python tests need to be disabled for an ORT wheel built with DML (and not CUDA) support because they are not supported by the DML EP or they don't pass some tests. 

We keep these tests covered for cases where both the DML EP and CUDA EP are built into the wheel (to have them covered in the CI pipelines which uses the combination). The tests will pass in CI because the CUDA EP has higher precedence than the DML EP and when all nodes are assigned to CUDA, these tests run fine. 

The problem is that there in nothing in CI that tests a "pure" DML only Python wheel (a real world user would build only this) and hence we won't catch any failures. Opened a backlog task (897037) to address this.

**Motivation and Context**
Fix https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5130

title: "Resize-11" ops with  "nearest neighbour" mode have unexpected behavior
body:
**Describe the bug**
For resize-11 ops, with "nearest neighbour" mode, the [coordinate transformation is applied to batch and channel dimension](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/upsample.cc#L174), while batch and channel are the same for input and output tensor, leading to data from one batch of input set to another batch of ouput.
Take an example, when inputShape is [B, C H W] == [4, 4, 10, 10], targetShape is [4, 4, 30, 30], "coordinate_transform_mode" is "TF_HALF_PIXEL_FOR_NN", "nearest_mode_name" is "ceil". For batch dimension, the first batch's transformed position is (0 + 0.5) / 1.f = 0.5, after round by "ceil" , it's 1(second batch). That means we set data to first batch with data from second batch. Is this an expected behaviour? 
For [other mode](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/upsample.cc#L398) or "[nearest neighbour" with scale 2x](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/upsample.cc#L53). Coordinate transformation is not applied to the batch and channel dimension.

**Urgency**
Urgent

**System information**
- all

**Expected behavior**
Coordinate transformation should not be applied to the batch and channel(scale == 1.0f) dimension. This is a nature behaviour and seemed the behavior of other platform(TF, pytorch...).

title: CPU QLinearConv supporting per-channel quantized weights
body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
I see that the [quantization tool](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization) has support for performing per-output-channel quantization. However, it does not seem as though the CPU `QLinearConv` kernel supports these per-channel quantized weight tensors yet, as running such a model results in

```
filter zero point must be a scalar or 1D tensor of size 1
```

and indeed currently the kernel implementation is hard-coded to only support a single scalar output scale & zero-point, which would prevent use of per-channel quantization. 

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/8fa427b264e00fb9e8a2f2b03ca78e808f0d0609/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/nn/qlinearconv.cc#L45

and it also does not seem straightforward to modify the existing implementation of `QLinearConv` since the output is computed one conv group at a time (i.e. populating outermost dimension `M/conv_group` at each matmul).

Is there any plans to update the kernel definition to allow for use of per-channel quantization?

**Describe the solution you'd like**
A means of performing inference using per-channel quantized operators

title: NCHWc optimizer fixes for quantized models
body:
**Description**: This updates the NCHWc transformer to not interfere with quantized convolution models, based on observations from internal models.

**Motivation and Context**
The MaxPool transformation in the NCHWc transformer didn't check the type of the input tensor, so it incorrectly altered a quantized CNN that contained MaxPool<uint8_t>. Added checks for this and a test case.

The optimizer also has been changed to not force a reorder to NCHWc for GlobalAveragePool/GlobalMaxPool. Typically for float32 CNNs, the tensor is already in NCHWc format and the runtime should avoid going back to NCHW to do this operation. But for a quantized CNN, the float tensor usually came from a DequantizeLinear. It's cheaper to run the NCHW version of GlobalAveragePool/GlobalMaxPool instead. This saves a few % for one quantized CNN. MaxPool/AveragePool behavior is unchanged for now.
